rmer president of the Constitutional Council in France; Stephen Breyer, Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States; Antonio Cassese, the first president of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia; Dieter Grimm, former vice president of the Constitutional Court of Germany; Gil Carlos Rodriguez, president of the Court of Justice of the European Union; and Ronald Dworkin, formerly of Oxford University, now professor of philosophy and law at the New York University Law School. What followed was an animated discussion ranging from the influence of the media on the judiciary to the development of an international criminal law to the judge's consideration of the judge's own role. Judges in Contemporary Democracy offers a rare and intimate glimpse into the powers and the role of judges in today's society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJudges. 0aJudgments. 0aJudicial process. 0aPolitical questions and judicial power. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aBadinter, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadinter, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBreyer, Justice Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBreyer, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassese, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDworkin, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimm, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodriguez Iglesias, Gil Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814739